{After} 1. e4 e6 2. d3 d5 {White can support his pawn on e4 with either 3 Nd2
or 3 Qe2. Both are equally good moves, with advantages and drawbacks relative
to each other. Thus putting the knight on d2 is a valuable developing move,
while leaving it on b1 for a while gives an additional attacking option in the
main line if Black castles queenside. On e2 the queen not only defends e4, she
supports an e4-e5 thrust, but she might also become a target of a ...Ba6 move
in the future (that is, if Black plays ...d5xe4; d3xe4 b6 and ...Ba6 as in
Game 7).} 3. -- ({In Part One we examine the main line with} 3. Nd2 {, when
after} Nf6 4. g3 c5 5. Bg2 Nc6 6. Ngf3 Be7 7. O-O {Black has a big choice to
make. Should he castle kingside or play} b6 {to fianchetto his queen's bishop,
which is normally followed by queenside castling?}) ({The subject of Part Two
is White's important alternative} 3. Qe2 {. The main line is similar to that
in Part One, with a key moment being reached in Game Four after} Nf6 4. Nf3 Be7
5. g3 c5 6. Bg2 Nc6 7. O-O b6 8. e5 Nd7 9. h4 Bb7 10. c3 Qc7 11. Re1 h6 {.
Here White can try to benefit from the delayed development of his knight with}
12. Na3 $1 {.}) ({In Part Three we investigate the alternative deployment of
Black's bishop to d6 in the sequence} 3. Nd2 c5 4. Ngf3 Nc6 5. g3 Bd6 {.} ({
Rather than straightforward development with} 5... Nf6 {and 6...Be7, Black
uses the bishop to oppose White's space gaining e4-e5 advance.})) ({Part Four
features variations in which Black plays (in either order as appropriate) ...d5xe4 and ...e6-e5 to equalize the space balance. This approach is possible
against both the 3 Nd2 and 3 Qe2 scenarios, and so they are discussed together
in Game 6 which begins} 3. Qe2 Nc6 4. Nf3 e5 5. g3 dxe4 6. dxe4 Nf6 7. Bg2 Bc5
{.}) ({Finally, in Part Five we look at} 3. Qe2 dxe4 4. dxe4 b6 {in which
Black hopes to profit by harassing the white queen with ...Ba6.}) *

