dxe4 e5 18. Nf3 $1 {Played according to Philidor's precept that the pieces are
the servants of the pawns.} ({Instead of putting his knight on a strong
attacking square with} 18. Nf5 {, when} Bf6 {maintains the black centre,
Nimzowitsch is keen to remove the strongpoint on e5 which is acting as a
barrier to the mobility of his kingside pawns.}) 18... exf4 19. gxf4 Rfe8 ({
Naturally if} 19... Qxf4 20. Ne5 {wins a piece, but now the white centre is
gathering steam.}) 20. e5 Nc5 21. Nd4 Ne6 22. Rad1 $1 {Developing and
supporting the knight on d4.} ({After} 22. Nxe6 $6 fxe6 {the pawn on e6 is a
new barrier to the white kingside pawns.}) 22... Nxd4 23. Bxd4 Bf5 {EXERCISE:
Knowing that Nimzowitsch wants to remove all the obstacles in the way of his
kingside pawns, can you suggest a good move for him? --- ANSWER:} 24. Be4 $1 {
Exactly. The exchange of light-squared bishops clears the way for a pawn
rampage.} Bxe4+ 25. Qxe4 Rad8 26. e6 Bf8 27. Be5 $6 {Too much of a hurry.} ({
Simply} 27. f5 {is strong.}) 27... Qc8 ({Black could escape with} 27... Rxd1
28. Rxd1 Qe7 $1 {Yes, it's easy to be a tactical god when you have a computer
program.} ({But not} 28... Rxe6 29. Bxc7 Rxe4 30. Rd8 {when there is no good
way to stop 31 Bd6, winning a piece due to the pin.})) 28. f5 fxe6 ({He had to
play} 28... Rxd1 {at once, when} 29. Rxd1 fxe6 30. f6 {is still scary, but} Rd8
{should hold.}) 29. f6 $1 Rxd1 30. f7+ $1 {In similar scenarios the f-pawn is
used as a battering ram to shatter Black's defences on the f-file or g-file,
but here it is enough for it to take away the g8-square from the black king.}
Kh8 31. Rxd1 Rd8 32. Qg6 $1 {For once White's dark-squared bishop rather than
its light-squared cousin is the hero in the King's Indian Attack.} ({Black can
give a couple of checks, including the big one} 32. Qg6 Rxd1+ {, but once they
run out White will play Qxh6 mate.}) 1-0

