{No pottering around!} 1. Nf3 {It's difficult to find a quiet yet effective
approach for White against the Dutch (and I'm not just saying that because I
play it myself as Black). The problem is that lines that preserve a King's
Indian Attack 'flavour' - restrained pawn play, methodical development,
avoiding an immediate clash in the centre - are exactly what the Dutch excels
against. Bent Larsen said he always liked to play the Dutch against players
who 'potter around', playing tame and inoffensive moves while Black builds up
an attack.} -- ({The delayed Lisitsin Gambit: So we had better try something
active. I recommend the popular delayed form of the Lisitsin Gambit versus the
Dutch, namely} 1... f5 2. d3 {and then against virtually anything, let's say}
d6 {,} 3. e4 {(the Lisitsin proper is 1 Nf3 f5 2 e4!?). --- White challenges
Black's f5-pawn. He will try to dissolve the centre in such a way that he
profits from his lead in development and the fact that Black's light squares
have been loosened. We'll look at three examples in which Black's resistance
becoming ever tougher. --- You will be obliged to learn a couple of long
forcing variations, but you should be well rewarded for your trouble as Black
doesn't seem to be able to equalize.}) ({A note about move order: The games
below after 1 Nf3 feature the immediate 1...f5. However, Black could play} 1...
e6 {and after} 2. g3 ({playing the immediate} 2. d3 {seems a simple way to
avoid the whole issue, when} f5 3. e4 {looks grotty for Black}) 2... f5 {,
when he has got a Dutch whilst avoiding the 2 d3 and 3 e4 line. Most Dutch
players want a Leningrad rather than a Classical Dutch or Stonewall Dutch, so
are unlikely to adopt this move order.}) ({Also possible is} 1... d6 {, so
that if 2 g3 f5 takes us out of Dutch preparation. So again} 2. d3 {should be
preferred} -- ({, when} 2... f5 3. e4 e5 4. Nc3 {is our familiar line.}) ({.
Black might prefer} 2... e5 3. -- ({, so that after} 3. g3 f5 4. c4 {he has
got in his active ...f7-f5 'Dutch' move whilst we have been 'pottering around'
in Larsen's phrase.}) ({. Instead, after 2...e5 you could reply} 3. e4 {when if
} f5 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. exf5 Bxf5 6. d4 {brings us back into the territory of the
delayed Lisitsin - see Game 40, the version with 4...Nf6.}) ({Instead, Black
can give up on the Dutch (after} 3. e4 {), and direct play into a King's
Indian Defence with a symmetrical position after} Nf6 4. g3 g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 6.
O-O O-O {, etc - see Game 41.} (6... --)))) ({The King's Indian Attack versus
the King's Indian Defence: If White wants the King's Indian Attack, and Black
wants the King's Indian Defence, and neither player backs down, then you get} 
1... Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. d3 d6 6. e4 e5 {. This symmetrical
position is rather uncommon in tournament play. It is safe enough for Black,
but there's always a danger of a restless King's Indian Defence devotee
overpressing as in Game 41.}) *

